<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-persona-building">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Fully automated persona generation for 1,000+ users: Haiku ingests exports, Opus validates clusters, Sonnet transforms to JSON documents.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>personas</tag>
      <tag>clustering</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>agent-workflow</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI Persona Building (Automated Pipeline)</title>

    <summary>Fully automated end-to-end persona generation for large user datasets (1,000+ users): Haiku ingests behavioral event exports via API, Opus validates cluster separability, Sonnet transforms clusters into JSON persona documents consumable by downstream agents. Human approval gate sits between Opus and Sonnet.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>At scale, manual review of clustering is infeasible. Automated pipelines enable monthly persona refresh but introduce new risks: silent schema breakage, weak-cluster propagation, and JTBD statements fabricated from behavioral data alone. Silhouette scoring, schema validation, and mandatory human gates prevent the most dangerous failure mode — confident wrong personas adopted without scrutiny.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Automating persona generation as part of a recurring research pipeline (monthly cohort refresh).</item>
        <item>Building personas programmatically from large datasets where manual review of clustering is infeasible.</item>
        <item>Running JTBD map generation at scale across multiple product areas simultaneously.</item>
        <item>Integrating persona data into a downstream agent (copywriting, feature-priority) via stable JSON schema.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-off persona creation for a single product decision — use ai-assisted-persona-building with direct team involvement.</item>
        <item>When data quality is unknown — run a data audit before feeding into the pipeline.</item>
        <item>When personas will be presented to external stakeholders without human review of the narrative layer.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="pipeline-architecture">
      <p>Four stages: Haiku ingests behavioral event exports via API and normalizes to feature matrix; Opus validates cluster separability; human approval gate; Sonnet transforms validated clusters into persona JSON documents consumable by downstream agents.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Store the persona JSON schema in version control; downstream agents depend on a stable schema and schema changes break them silently.</statement>
        <rationale>Downstream agents (copywriting, feature-priority, pricing) consume persona data as structured input. Unversioned schema changes break their prompts without surfacing an error.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Add schema validation at the pipeline entry point (analytics export ingestion); schema changes in Amplitude, Mixpanel, or Heap exports silently break normalization.</statement>
        <rationale>Analytics platforms change their export format without notice. Validation at ingestion surfaces the break immediately rather than propagating corrupted data through clustering and narrative stages.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set a persona refresh cadence (monthly or quarterly) and automate drift detection by comparing new cluster centroids against stored ones; flag centroid shift over 15% for human review.</statement>
        <rationale>User behavior drifts with product changes and market shifts. Automated drift detection prevents stale personas from accumulating in downstream systems undetected.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="governance-for-automated-pipelines">
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep a persona changelog with date, data snapshot version, k, silhouette score, and a one-line summary of what changed each cycle.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a changelog, persona evolution is invisible. Auditors and stakeholders cannot determine when a persona changed or why, making trust impossible to maintain.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Human approval gate between Opus (cluster validation) and Sonnet (narrative generation) is non-negotiable even in fully automated pipelines.</statement>
        <rationale>A bad cluster produces a confidently-written persona that enters downstream systems without scrutiny. The gate is the single control that prevents confident-wrong output from propagating.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="differences-from-interactive-persona-building">
      <list>
        <item>Scale: automated pipeline targets 1,000+ users where manual cluster review is infeasible</item>
        <item>Schema: outputs must conform to a stable JSON schema for downstream agent consumption</item>
        <item>Drift detection: recurring pipeline includes centroid comparison against stored baseline</item>
        <item>Risk: removing human review from any stage produces confident wrong personas — the gate must be enforced even at scale</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-roles">
      <rule>
        <statement>Haiku: ingest behavioral event exports via API, normalize to feature matrix, compute cluster centroids. Do not delegate normalization to Sonnet or Opus.</statement>
        <rationale>Normalization is mechanical and deterministic. Using higher-capability models for mechanical data processing wastes cost without quality benefit.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Opus: validate cluster separability (silhouette score), generate cluster report, flag fragile clusters (under 50 users) and redundant clusters (over 70% feature overlap).</statement>
        <rationale>Cluster boundary identification requires reasoning about feature distributions; Opus provides the analytical depth needed for reliable cluster quality assessment.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Sonnet: generate persona narratives, JTBD maps, and pain-point summaries only after human approval of Opus cluster report.</statement>
        <rationale>Narrative generation is expensive to redo. Running Sonnet before human approval of clusters wastes tokens and produces personas built on potentially invalid segments.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="silhouette-gate">
      <rule>
        <statement>When silhouette scores are below 0.25, the pipeline must abort and surface the issue rather than proceeding to narrative generation.</statement>
        <rationale>Pipeline auto-retry on weak clusters compounds the error. Weak clusters produce personas with confidence language that stakeholders accept uncritically.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run clustering with at least 3 different random seeds; if membership changes significantly across seeds, reject the k and flag for human data review.</statement>
        <rationale>Unstable clusters signal that the feature set does not support the chosen segmentation. The solution is better feature engineering, not narrative generation from bad segments.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="gotchas">
      <rule>
        <statement>Agents generating JTBD statements from behavioral data without qualitative input produce feature descriptions dressed as motivations; require an "inferred" tag or reject.</statement>
        <rationale>JTBD requires motivation (why), which is absent from analytics exports. Behavioral data alone produces statements like "wants to export data" when the real motivation is unstated.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Fully automated pipeline without a human gate between clustering and narrative generation is high-risk: a bad cluster produces a confidently-written persona that gets adopted without scrutiny.</statement>
        <rationale>The entire value of data-driven personas collapses if the segments are invalid. The human gate is the last control before personas enter production systems.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Always run silhouette scoring or elbow method before fixing k — never accept an agent's arbitrary k choice</item>
        <item>Store the persona JSON schema in version control; downstream agents depend on a stable schema and schema changes break them silently</item>
        <item>Tag each persona attribute as data_derived or assumed; downstream agents must not treat assumed attributes as facts</item>
        <item>Set a persona refresh cadence (monthly or quarterly) and automate drift detection by comparing new cluster centroids against stored ones; flag greater than 15% centroid shift for human review</item>
        <item>Keep a persona changelog: date, data snapshot version, k, silhouette score, and a one-line summary of what changed</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A fully automated pipeline: Haiku ingests behavioral event exports via API (Amplitude, Mixpanel, Heap), normalizes them to a feature matrix, and computes cluster centroids. Opus validates cluster separability and generates a cluster report. Sonnet transforms validated clusters into persona documents, JTBD maps per persona, and a pain-point summary. Results are written to a JSON schema that downstream agents (copywriting, feature-priority) can consume directly. A human approval gate sits between Opus (cluster validation) and Sonnet (narrative generation).</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent (manages the multi-stage pipeline with quality gates and retry logic), General Claude subagent (Haiku) for data ingestion, normalization, feature matrix construction, General Claude subagent (Opus) for cluster separability analysis, coverage validation, governance checks, and General Claude subagent (Sonnet) for persona narrative, JTBD statements, pain-point summary generation.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>Python + scikit-learn: K-means, DBSCAN, silhouette scoring for cluster validation (pip install scikit-learn pandas numpy)</item>
        <item>Python + umap-learn: UMAP dimensionality reduction for visualization (pip install umap-learn matplotlib)</item>
        <item>Amplitude Data Export API: Pull user-level event data for clustering (developers.amplitude.com/docs/export-api)</item>
        <item>Mixpanel Export API: Pull raw event streams per user (developer.mixpanel.com/reference/export)</item>
        <item>Heap Connect: Export behavioral data to S3/warehouse (heap.io/docs/heap-connect)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Amplitude (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes API): Best-in-class behavioral export; cohort API; Amplitude AI persona suggestions</item>
        <item>Mixpanel (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes API): Strong for event-level export; JQL for custom behavioral queries</item>
        <item>Heap (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes API): Auto-capture reduces instrumentation gaps; Heap Connect exports to data warehouse</item>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes API): Qualitative layer; attach interview clips to persona attributes</item>
        <item>Segment (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes API): CDP; aggregates behavioral data from all sources into one schema</item>
        <item>dbt (OSS, Agent-friendly: Yes CLI): Transform raw event data into clustering-ready feature tables</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/validate-clusters.py" purpose="Silhouette scoring across k range; recommends optimal k; flags weak clusters"/>
      <template path="templates/persona-schema-prompt.txt" purpose="Prompt for generating structured persona JSON including data_confidence and assumptions fields"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
